# TOAST PROTOCOL

The parent skill (`/c-yesterday`) invokes this file on every fire. Execute the three protocols IN ORDER. Each protocol is stateful — read sections below, mutate sections below, save file.

---

## Protocol 1 — Job List Mirror (staleness check)

```
STEP 1: Open this file. Locate "## JOB LIST MIRROR" section.
STEP 2: If the section body is empty OR the "mirror_timestamp" field is missing OR mirror_timestamp is > 72h old:
          GOTO STEP 3 (refresh).
        ELSE:
          GOTO Protocol 2 (skip refresh).
STEP 3: Pull the current job board from the most recent conversation paste
        OR from Chad's c-chads-dreams board source.
        Expected categories (preserve order + color dots + ✅ markers):
          - Work Progress
          - Work Debt
          - Personal & Family
          - Finance
          - Vietnam
          - Tech Partnerships
          - Work Dreams
STEP 4: Overwrite the "## JOB LIST MIRROR" section body with the fresh list.
STEP 5: Set mirror_timestamp = <now ISO8601> at top of JOB LIST MIRROR section.
STEP 6: Append a one-line entry to "## NOTES LOG": "[<ts>] mirror refreshed — N jobs across 7 categories".
```

---

## Protocol 2 — New Job Catcher (low-token)

```
STEP 1: Load the JOB LIST MIRROR section into memory as a SET of normalized job titles
        (lowercase, strip emoji/dots/checkmarks/whitespace).
STEP 2: Scan ONLY the last 3 days of chat context already available in the current
        /c-yesterday invocation. DO NOT spawn new searches. DO NOT re-read archives.
        (This keeps token cost near-zero — reuse what the parent skill already loaded.)
STEP 3: Extract candidate jobs using these triggers:
          - "new job:", "add to board", "put this on the list"
          - "I need to", "gotta", "todo", "remember to"
          - explicit board-category mentions followed by a new item
STEP 4: For each candidate, normalize the title and check membership against STEP 1 set.
          - If already in mirror → discard.
          - If NOT in mirror → append to "## NEW JOBS QUEUE" with:
              [<ts>] category_guess: "<Work Progress|Work Debt|...>" | title: "<short>"
STEP 5: Cap the queue at 10 entries. If >10, drop the oldest.
STEP 6: Append one-line entry to NOTES LOG: "[<ts>] catcher ran — K candidates, M new queued".
```

Expected delta per fire: 0–2. If K > 5 on a single run, log an edge-case flag in NOTES LOG.

---

## Protocol 3 — Notes Log

```
STEP 1: On every invocation, append a dated line to "## NOTES LOG".
STEP 2: Entries should include (when relevant):
          - timestamp of run
          - which protocols fired vs skipped
          - approx token budget used by this support file
          - any parse failures, empty scans, or category guesses that were ambiguous
          - promotions from NEW JOBS QUEUE → JOB LIST MIRROR (when Chad confirms)
STEP 3: Keep the log rolling. Trim to last 50 entries to prevent bloat.
```

---

## Protocol 4 — Pinned Jobs

```
STEP 1: On every fire, read ## PINNED JOBS (inside # CACHED VIEWS).
STEP 2: Render those rows at the TOP of the QAL output with 📌 marker,
        separated from the main list by a divider line.
        Pinned rows do NOT count toward total_sessions.
STEP 3: Pinned jobs are maintained MANUALLY by Chad — the skill does NOT
        auto-populate them. They persist until Chad removes or moves them.
STEP 4: To add a pinned job, Chad says "pin [job]" or "add to top" —
        append an entry to ## PINNED JOBS in the format:
          N. 📌 <job title> — <status dot> <status label>
STEP 5: When a pinned job is completed or deprioritized, Chad manually
        removes or relocates the entry. Skill does NOT auto-expire pins.
STEP 6: Soft cap = 5 pinned jobs. If ## PINNED JOBS has >5 entries,
        log a warning in NOTES LOG: "[<ts>] pin cap exceeded — N pins active".
```

